I'm a bit out of my league there cause I know this simple looking code is probably some of the soup that makes d3 so easy to use.  I'm not going try to solve it but I know that removing the semi-colon 
        if (next && node.compareDocumentPosition(next) ^ 4) next.parentNode.insertBefore(node, next);
makes all the red go away =D in my browser.

Also, this goes back as far as 6 and is not caused by the minified code sadly it is a bug.

```
function selection_order() {

  for (var groups = this._groups, j = -1, m = groups.length; ++j < m;) {
    for (var group = groups[j], i = group.length - 1, next = group[i], node; --i >= 0;) {
      if (node = group[i]) {
        if (next && node.compareDocumentPosition(next) ^ 4) next.parentNode.insertBefore(node, next);
        next = node;
      }
    }
  }

  return this;
}
```

